Literature Review

Individuals have some agency regarding who they choose to associate with. While the utility of numerous weak ties has been explored(Granovetter 1973), individuals will likely invest more heavily in some relationships over others. The selection of these close associates can be based on homophily(???), or necessity(???). Regardless of reason, trusting relationships are understood to facilitate the transmission of resources between individuals(???). One example of this exists within the co-authorship networks of academia. Co-authorship networks differ structurally across disciplines(Newman 2004). Researchers tend to coauthor with colleges wit similar research interests, while they predominately only cite those with differing interests(???).

Methods

We used a pseudo Temporal Exponential Random Graph Model (TERGM) to model network formation. We start with a number of isolates (\(\alpha\)), and a set number of iterations (t). At time = t, we randomly allow each node to initiate a connection with another node. If a node already has a partner, it is not eligible to be paired with. At time = t + 1, each of these connections are tested for affinity (trust). If both nodes are of the same sub-type, the connection is solidified as a trusting relationship. If nodes are of a different sub-type, the connection is dropped.
